content.description: a lot of right facing holds
content.location: left most of the short routes

content.description:
Fun, somewhat technical in a couple of places, with an enjoyable, crimpy finish on a beautiful piece of limestone below the chains.

Rated 5.7 by the FA; most think it's a number or two harder.
content.location:
Just to the left of the trough containing

Helga the Berner

.

Alternatively, two routes left of

Norma Brow

which is the right-most route of those that start on the smaller shelf.

content.description: fun route
content.location: Left most of the first (short) routes that the trail arrives at.

content.description: Shares the first 5 bolts with Radiance then splits right.  Few tricky moves under and through the roof on manufactured/reinforced holds gets you onto the headwall and some funky climbing on sharp stone up the arete.  Chains just to teh right of the Radiance.

Fairly challenging for the low end of .10; this line has a little bit of everything.

Start up through the first few bolts with an occasional pocket to a section of rounded sidepulls with less-than-optimal feet. Some fun, big moves await for a bolt or two, followed by an unnerving, delicate-yet-rather-pumpy sequence of moves that find you traversing to the right as you follow the bolt line.

Finally, an enjoyable open book allows stemming (or face climbing) through the last couple of bolts to the anchors.
content.location: This line starts just below where the trail turns briefly steeper as the trail heads up towards the west-facing wall.

content.description: A thin, nerve-wracking start through several somewhat-sparse-feeling bolts leads to briefly easier ground. The next order of business is unlocking a burly, exciting roof, followed by hanging on to the end while the pump gradually subsides.
content.protection: Nine bolts and anchors. If you used a stickclip on the first bolt you wouldn't be the first.
content.location: Starts midway up the steeper section of trail at the far right side of the south-facing wall.

content.description:
A fun corner problem with jugs, stemming, and a couple of thinking cap moves.

From the ground the route actually doesn't look like much, but it's definitely worth climbing.
content.location: In the right-facing corner at the far right of the south-facing wall. One must climb up towards the west-facing wall and then back to the corner.

content.description: A really, really fun line. A thin start (shared with the route to the left). After two bolts traverse right, following a crack using underclingery. After a couple of bolts, head up into a trough that turns into a crack. Jamming for the last few bolts if you want it, but not required.
content.location:
Starts from a ledge on the left side of the trail (when heading deeper into the crag) that sits above a 10 foot vertical face. Access to the ledge is via easy scrambling at the left side. Don't confuse this ledge with the much wider and higher ledge further along the trail.

The second-from-the-left route of four lines that start from the ledge.

content.description:
Juggy and thuggy; what's not to like?

This route is a hoot; one or two balancy, somewhat frightening moves after leaving the ground and then some pumpy jug-hauling over a lip to the chains.
content.location:
First line right of the right-facing corner containing

Sunday in the Park

. Heads up and right.

One must climb up towards the west-facing wall and then back towards the right end of the south-facing wall.

content.description:
A long, mostly casual jaunt to obvious chains hanging from a roof.

However, if you're of average height or less there is a move or two that you might find surprisingly difficult for "5.6."
content.protection: 11 bolts, chain anchors in a roof.
content.location:
On the left side of the south-facing wall; among the group of routes you first encounter when arriving at

The Hinterlands

.

Not counting

City Limits

(.11d) which starts uphill and around to the left a bit, this is the fourth route from the left (a few new routes were put in after Kory created his

This is the first wall that you come to after the hike.  City Limits is to the left, up a little ways from the main trail.

).

It's obvious because of its unusual chains hanging from the root.

content.description:
A challenging line in three distinct sections. Start up on less-than-vertical limestone which gets steeper and thinner as you go. An initial crux consists of figuring out how to use what thin, tiny bits there are.

After surmounting the first thin bit (and heading left after the fifth bolt), a rest awaits as you contemplate a steepening section through the obvious roof.

After the roof use your resting skills to turn down the pump, and then head up another thin, slabby section until you really start to wonder who stole all the holds.
content.location:
Starts below an obvious, dark roof and right-facing bulge. The first five bolts are shared with

Unemployment Line

, a .12a that branches right.

content.description:
Another of the long, enjoyable routes at

Hinterlands

this route is similar to its neighbor to the left, but different enough to make it worth while.

Head up the through the first four bolts and branch right (really more-or-less straight up). Head up through terrain varying from occasional jugs to not much of anything.

Note that although the topo shows this route ending on the anchors for

The Illustrious One

it has its own anchors.
content.location:
The first line of bolts to the right of the large ledge that is approached via any of several easier routes (and one stiff .11a).

Phosphorescence

branches right after the fourth bolt.

content.description:
A long, occasionally tricky frolic up steep, bulletproof limestone in a great setting.

A steep, thin start of the ledge initially gets your attention, followed by some non-trivial but quite enjoyable, mostly cruiser moves through a couple of bolts. Some thinner bits await, with some very interesting terrain containing odd pockets through the last few bolts
content.location:
The line starts from a wide, sloping ledge that must be approached via any of several short lines.

The Peach

is the middle of the three lines that start up the ledge and shares its first bolt (and second bolt if you want it) with a 5.7 that heads up the corner on the right.

content.description:
A thin start from the ledge through two bolts and then up and left towards the arete. A thin, somewhat perplexing crux leads to big, fun moves afterwards. Keep the pump at bay until the chains.

Shares the first two bolts with

Solar Flare

.
content.location:
Starts from a ledge on the left side of the trail (when heading deeper into the crag) that sits above a 10 foot vertical face. Access to the ledge is via easy scrambling at the left side. Don't confuse this ledge with the much wider and higher ledge further along the trail.

The left-most route of four lines that start from the ledge.

content.description: Edgy, crimpy, sharp limestone. Overall, not my favorite route by a long shot. Dark, spikey limestone marks this route.
content.location: First route after the overhanging arete as you progress toward the west wall.

content.description:
A long, very enjoyable route with a number of challenging moves, capped with a thin, flummoxing section right before the chains.

Head up the through the first four bolts and branch left. A few steeper bits interspersed with occasional mini-ledges for feet keep your heart going. A bit past halfway a slightly less steep section briefly intervenes.

The line then gets gradually thinner until right near the top you're left wondering how you're going to possibly finish this thing before the pump overtakes you and you peel.
content.location:
The first line of bolts to the right of the large ledge that is approached via any of several easier routes (and one stiff .11a).

The Illustrious One

branches left after the fourth bolt.

Shares first 4 bolts with

Phosphoresence

.

content.description: A fun, cerebral start on less-than-obvious holds leads to some jugs for a reasonable rest. Next up are some strenuous moves that lead to a large, oblong pocket. A non-obvious and unlikely series of moves gets you through the crux. Try not to fall off after the crux because you're pumped.
content.location:
Starts from a ledge on the left side of the trail (when heading deeper into the crag) that sits above a 10 foot vertical face. Access to the ledge is via easy scrambling at the left side. Don't confuse this ledge with the much wider and higher ledge further along the trail.

The second-from-the-right route of four lines that start from the ledge.

content.description: From the ledge make an easy start (but don't slip) to the first bolt. Follow the jugs and stems upward. Just before the last bolt, there are two cracks and an almost-chimney to the very left. Stay towards the right two cracks and go up towards the bolt. Sometimes the far right crack can have water running in it, so it's the harder of the moves on the climb, definitely making it the crux. Use a long anchor to avoid mild rope drag if anyone is top roping after.
content.location:
Starts from a ledge on the left side of the trail (when heading deeper into the crag) that sits above a 10 foot vertical face. Access to the ledge is via easy scrambling at the left side. Don't confuse this ledge with the much wider and higher ledge further along the trail.

The right-most of four lines that start from the ledge.

content.description:
Start off on good feet and head up through a mix of small edges and jugs to an easy stemming section that is slightly runout due  to hollow rock.

Pull through jugs to reach a dihedral that can be handled with some combination of laybacking, stemming, maybe throw in a hand jam.

Reach up and pull over the positive lip above, you're pretty much done.
content.location: left of Norma Brow, right of Wake and Bake

content.description:
A fun run up a steep face above a wide ledge.

Head up from the ledge through varying terrain, looking about for the good holds which will appear just as you despair. A thin section near the top may be a tad challenging for the edging-imparied.
content.location:
The line starts from a wide, sloping ledge that must be approached via any of several short lines.

Enlightenment

is the left-most line that starts from the ledge.

content.description: 35 feet

This fun bit of technical trickery starts below a small roof/bulge and then heads to the left of the roof bit before trending back to the right. After some thin, committing moves that travel to a set of decent hand holds, you're left wondering how you're going to get past the next steep bit which has an apparent dearth of holds.

Figure this out, then reward yourself with fun moves to the chains.
content.location: Starts below and to the right of the ledge from which the four routes including Solar Flare and Hinterlander start.

content.description: According to the beta photo, this is 5.4, but when we climbed it, it was DEFINITELY not 5.4. Not hard, by any means, but certainly not 5.4. Dirty rock. Not great climbing. More of a stepping stone to get up to the fun routes up above.
content.location: On the same feature as Lords of the Night, but around a little corner.
